d in a speech of considerable\nlength^ delivered last month, devoted\nto an appeal for statehood for New\nMex. co and territorial government for\nfor Ala*ka.\n\"Mr. Speaker,\" he said, \"congresa\nis too big a body, too busy as a legis\nlative forum with the momentous affairs\nof the oatiou toUct as a board of aider\nmen for Aiaski, for New Mexico, for\nArizona.\"\nIt is a member of that forum that so\nspeaks and be knows. It is the whole\ncase. Congress, each member be\nplagued by his constituents to secure\nfor them the thing they want, how c40\nthey have time to thick if us or to\nrealiz? our neei'sV Mr. Su zer, him\nself, has personal mining Interests in\nAlaska, ihi re is a town named after\nhim; be has been here many times\nand his sympathies, the efore, are with\nus and his voice is raised iu our behalf,\nbut it is the only voice th it is ever\nraised in intelligent sympathy. Con\ngress is legitimately a board of alder\nmen for the l):strict of Columbia? its\n)rtcul legislature? bet how silly to ex\nRaw Furs....\nHigh Prices for Fine furs\nPercy's Fur House\nEstablished 1897\nPhil Abrahams\nReal Estate\nBROKER\nCollections\nNOTARY PUBLIC\n52 *X)UKTH AVE., SKAOWAY\nWE PAY\nWrite For Price List\nshko?t>. Wisconsin\npeel the big body to aot in the same\ncapacity (or Alaska ot which it has no\nslight conception.\"\nContinuing Mr. Sul/er said: \"Why\nnot give iheoi what they are entitled\nto, and let them legislate for them\nselves? The principles of local self*\ngovernment are dear to tbe American\nheart. The.v constitute the corner\nstone of the American Republic\nThe |>eople of Alaska\nare entitled to territorial government.\nThey want to make their own local\nlaws sud not bother congress, and the\nonly way they can do so is through\nthe agency of territorial government.\nAfter a long'fijjht we dually succeeded\nIn passing a bill to give Alaska a dele\ngate in congress, de is here in the\nperson of Hon. Thomas Cale one of\nGod's noblemen--and he typifies the\nintelligence and the Industry and the\npatriotism of the people of Alaska, and\nyet what can he do here\nThe Alaskan has been asked to ex\nplain the meaulng of the expression,\n\"Hoggatt meu will undoubtedly be de\nnominated the convention,\" which oc\ncurred in a despatch from Chicago some\ndays ago, re the political situation.\nCertainly. .There were two republican\nconvention*. Technically there was\nbut one? there can bo but one, so far as\nthe national committee is concerned.\nBoth factions claim to be that one, but\nonly tbe national committee can decide\naud tbe important matter is even now\nbefore it for deteruiiuatiou. On this\ndetermination? whether \"the Hoggatts\nor the anti-Uoggalts constituted the\nconvention,\" rests the other important\nquestion, as to which shall control the\nrepublican organization in Alaska. It\nm >y br argued that tbe Alaskan\nshould not employ terms technical iu\ntheir character such as may not be un\nderstood by all. But how are such ever\nto learn-and Alaska is getting more and\nmore into politics, where these terms\nare employed. This argument, you\nsee, carried to its conclusion, would bar\nthe polite from the use of tbe alphabet.\nBut where uslDg- such t-rms the Alas\nkan will, upon request, always be will\ning 'o c xplain them.\nPRAIRIE DAWN\n(By Willa Sibert Gather.)\nA crimeou tire that vanquishes the\nstars:\nA pungent odor from the dusty snge;\nA sudden stirring of the huddled herds;\nA breaking of tbe distant table-lands\nThrough purple mists ascending, and\ntbe tlare\nOf water ditches silver lu the light;\nA swift, bright lance hurled low across\nthe world;\nA sudden sickne* for the hills of Home\nFrom April Twilight.\nBEAUTIFUL DAY IN WHICH SO\nJOURNERS MAY MAKE THE BEST\nOF THEIR DELAY\ni|! LOW WATER AT WHITEHOftSE jij\n???iiiii8ni?ii???in??M?????imm)i\nThe result of the obaerrttloo taken\nat Moore wharf at midnight, June 7\n190*, la a* follows*.\nTemperature time obaervat'n..63*abovo\nMax. temp. preceding 24 hours.